editorial:
**Greedy — two-pointer sweep**: Sort `arrivals` and `departures` independently. Use `i = 0` over arrivals and `j = 0` over departures. Track `inUse` and `peak`. While `i < n`:
- If `arrivals[i] <= departures[j]`: a cab arrives before/at the next departure, so we need one more bay (`inUse++; i++; peak = max(peak, inUse)`).
- Else: a cab departs first, so a bay frees (`inUse--; j++`).

**Why greedy works (exchange argument)**: At any moment the number of bays in use equals (number of arrivals so far) - (number of departures so far). The maximum of this quantity over time is the answer. Sorting both arrays and walking with two pointers computes exactly that running count without needing the original (arrival, departure) pairing — pairings can be swapped freely without changing how many bays are simultaneously occupied.

```javascript
function minCabBays(arrivals, departures) {
  if (arrivals.length === 0) return 0;
  const a = [...arrivals].sort((x, y) => x - y);
  const d = [...departures].sort((x, y) => x - y);
  let i = 0, j = 0, inUse = 0, peak = 0;
  while (i < a.length) {
    if (a[i] <= d[j]) { inUse++; i++; if (inUse > peak) peak = inUse; }
    else { inUse--; j++; }
  }
  return peak;
}
```

**Time**: O(n log n). **Space**: O(n).

