editorial:
**Greedy — two passes**: Build two arrays.
- Left pass: `left[0] = 1`. For `i >= 1`, if `ratings[i] > ratings[i-1]` then `left[i] = left[i-1] + 1`, else `left[i] = 1`.
- Right pass: `right[n-1] = 1`. For `i < n-1`, if `ratings[i] > ratings[i+1]` then `right[i] = right[i+1] + 1`, else `right[i] = 1`.
The minimum candy at each index is `max(left[i], right[i])`. Sum these.

**Why greedy works (exchange argument)**: The constraint at each index is local — only depends on left and right neighbors. The left pass ensures every left-side constraint is satisfied minimally; the right pass does the same for right-side. Taking the max of the two is the smallest value satisfying both. Any solution at index `i` smaller than this max would violate a constraint, and any larger value is wasteful (we can decrease it without violating anything because no constraint depends on absolute counts, only on differences with strictly higher-rated neighbors).

```javascript
function diwaliCandyDistribution(ratings) {
  const n = ratings.length;
  if (n === 0) return 0;
  const left = new Array(n).fill(1);
  for (let i = 1; i < n; i++) if (ratings[i] > ratings[i - 1]) left[i] = left[i - 1] + 1;
  let total = 0;
  let right = 1;
  for (let i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    if (i < n - 1 && ratings[i] > ratings[i + 1]) right += 1;
    else right = 1;
    total += Math.max(left[i], right);
  }
  return total;
}
```

**Time**: O(n). **Space**: O(n).
